If you are a senior partner at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., you are not really=
 in it for the money. Oh, I mean, you=E2=80=99re in it for the money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0you get paid a lot, and you probably have an expensive lifestyle =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but you have already made a lot of money, you have marketabl=
e skills, you can afford to quit, and the money is not top of mind.
No, if you are a senior partner at Goldman, you are in it for the=C2=A0comm=
ittees. You have devoted much of your career to Goldman, and what you care =
about is your standing among the Goldman partnership, the respect that you =
get within the firm. And the surest indicator of that standing is what comm=
ittees you are on. Ideally you=E2=80=99d be on the management committee; th=
at=E2=80=99s the best committee, and being on that means that you are in th=
e inner circle of senior partners. But if you can=E2=80=99t be on the manag=
ement committee, there are some other good committees, and you=E2=80=99d li=
ke to at least be on them.
And there are very fine-grained forms of jealousy here. If you are the co-h=
ead of some important business, and you are not on a committee, and the oth=
er co-head of that business=C2=A0is=C2=A0on that committee, that is a morta=
l insult.  The Financial Times reports:

Two of Goldman Sachs=E2=80=99 top investment bankers have threatened to qui=
t after being excluded from a new operating committee established under chi=
ef executive David Solomon, according to people familiar with the matter.=
=C2=A0
Mark Sorrell, the London-based co-head of mergers and acquisitions and son =
of advertising executive Sir Martin Sorrell, and Gonzalo Garcia, co-head of=
 European investment banking, have told Goldman they may leave after being =
excluded from the committee, the people said.=C2=A0
Their respective co-heads =E2=80=94 Stephan Feldgoise in mergers and acquis=
itions and Anthony Gutman in European investment banking =E2=80=94 have bee=
n included in the committee, which has about a dozen members. ...
The source of the latest unrest is two new operating committees for investm=
ent banking and trading established by Solomon this year. They sit below Go=
ldman=E2=80=99s top-tier management committee.=C2=A0Both Sorrell and Garcia=
 were left out of the investment banking committee, the people said. ...
Conceived as a way to promote a new generation of leaders at Goldman and to=
 streamline decision making, the new committees have ruffled feathers inter=
nally about who was in or out, the people said. Conspicuously absent from t=
he committee in investment banking was anyone from Goldman=E2=80=99s equity=
 capital markets and real estate businesses.=C2=A0

Spectacular stuff, the most Goldman of all stories. Disclosure: I used to w=
ork at Goldman, and while=C2=A0I was very very far from being committee mat=
erial, this story resonates with me. If you work at Goldman and you turn to=
 your colleague and say =E2=80=9Cmy rival was just put on committee and I w=
as not, I think I have to quit,=E2=80=9D your colleague will nod solemnly a=
nd say =E2=80=9Cyes of course, we=E2=80=99ll miss you, but you=E2=80=99ve g=
ot to have principles.=E2=80=9D
Do you think they=E2=80=99ll quit? Do you think the threat will get them pu=
t on the committees? Also, if you are the CEO of Goldman you have all sorts=
 of opportunities to use committees tactically. Are you worried that too ma=
ny partners are leaving? Create some new committees and put lots of partner=
s on them; that will make them feel good. Do you=C2=A0want=C2=A0more disfav=
ored partners to leave? Create some new committees and leave those partners=
 off; they=E2=80=99ll quit in five minutes.=C2=A0

