<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">BOXX</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a while now people have emailed me occasio=
nally about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/344406=
18.286382/aHR0cHM6Ly9ldGZzaXRlLmFscGhhYXJjaGl0ZWN0LmNvbS9ib3h4Lw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBe3d95192" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> BOXX</a>, the Alpha Architect 1-3 Month B=
ox ETF, which is, loosely speaking, a money-market exchange-traded fund who=
se holders get paid Treasury bill interest rates=C2=A0but=C2=A0<em>don=E2=
=80=99t pay taxes</em>. I mean, that=E2=80=99s what it looks like on the ou=
tside. On the inside it=E2=80=99s a pile of stock options. =E2=80=9CIsn=E2=
=80=99t this cool,=E2=80=9D is how these emails often go. Or, =E2=80=9Cwhat=
 is going on here?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Zachary Mider <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34440618.286382/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjIvdGhpcy1leGNoYW5=
nZS10cmFkZWQtZnVuZC1taW1pY3MtdC1iaWxsLXJldHVybnMtd2l0aG91dC10YXgtYmlsbHM_Y2=
1waWQ9QkJEMDIyMjI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld=
3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBea6b4fdd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">  has an article explaining BOXX=E2=80=99s =
magic</a>, and it is very fun, and very much=C2=A0 up my alley, and if you =
are reading this column it=E2=80=99s probably very much up your alley as we=
ll:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A year-old investment fund offers returns that=
 closely track short-term Treasuries, with starkly lower tax bills. The fun=
d, Alpha Architect 1-3 Month Box ETF, uses a complex options strategy and a=
 longstanding tax loophole that favors exchange-traded funds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe spent seven years figuring out how=
 to do this,=E2=80=9D said Wesley Gray, the ex-Marine and chief executive o=
fficer of Alpha Architect. =E2=80=9CMy job is just to deliver all the value=
 I possibly can to my shareholders, within the law.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fund, known by its ticker BOXX, surpassed =
$1 billion in assets this month. It is one of a number of efforts to use th=
e ETF loophole in creative new ways, said Jeffrey Colon, a tax professor at=
 Fordham University=E2=80=99s School of Law in New York. He called BOXX =E2=
=80=9Cthe poster child for tax arbitrage.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>write a=
bout the poster child for tax arbitrage, can I?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The goal is pretty simple.=C2=A0You want somet=
hing close to a Treasury money-market fund: You want a place to park your m=
oney that pays roughly the current short-term Treasury interest rate, that =
is roughly as safe as short-term Treasury bills, and that will give you you=
r money back whenever you need it. You want it to be in the form of an exch=
ange-traded fund, so you can buy and sell shares on the stock exchange. And=
=C2=A0you want the tax treatment to be better than Treasury bills. Specific=
ally, you want the tax treatment that you=E2=80=99d typically get from a=C2=
=A0stock=C2=A0ETF: You don=E2=80=99t want to pay taxes until you=C2=A0sell =
your shares, and when you do, you want to pay capital gains taxes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the first thing you want to do is turn inte=
rest income into capital gains.=C2=A0In the US, interest income =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the interest you get paid on bonds or savings accounts or money marke=
t funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0is mostly taxed as ordinary income, at (federal) rat=
es of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34440618.286=
382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9maWxpbmcvZmVkZXJhbC1pbmNvbWUtdGF4LXJhdGVzLWF=
uZC1icmFja2V0cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB09bf4e06" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> up to 37%</a>. =
Long-term capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0your profits on selling assets that =
you=E2=80=99ve held for more than a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0are taxed at lower =
rates, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34440618.28=
6382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi90YXh0b3BpY3MvdGM0MDk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB718e9867" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> up to 20%</a>. Turning interest income into capital g=
ains is, therefore, good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense this should be=C2=A0<em>easy</em=
>.=C2=A0Interest is what you get paid for giving up the present use of your=
 money. If you put your money in a savings account, the bank pays you inter=
est every month for the use of your money. But if you buy, like, Nvidia Cor=
p. stock, or Bitcoin, nobody pays you any interest. Instead, you expect the=
 value of those things to go up over time, to compensate you for the use of=
 your money. If you put $100 into Nvidia today=C2=A0and sell it for $150 in=
 a year,=C2=A0part of that $50 is in some rough sense =E2=80=9Cinterest,=E2=
=80=9D compensation to you for giving up the use of your money for that yea=
r. Most of it, though, is =E2=80=9Crisk premium,=E2=80=9D compensation to y=
ou for taking the risk that Nvidia might go=C2=A0<em>down=C2=A0</em>instead=
. But there=E2=80=99s no actual division; it=E2=80=99s just $50 of capital =
gains.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course Nvidia really might go down inst=
ead. (Thus the risk premium.) So the job is to buy some asset that will app=
reciate, but only by the risk-free amount, and without risk: Instead of buy=
ing a stock that might go up 100% or down 50%, you want to buy an asset tha=
t will definitely go up exactly 5%. (I assume here that the short-term risk=
-free interest rate in the US is about 5%.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the simplest way you might imagine tur=
ning interest into capital gains.=C2=A0You give me $100 today, I promise to=
 pay you back $105 in a year and a day, and I=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<=
/em>pay you any interest along the way. =E2=80=9CNo interest income,=E2=80=
=9D you say to the Internal Revenue Service. And then in a year I give you =
back $105 and you say, well, I bought a bond for $100 and sold it for $105 =
after a year and a day, so I have $5 of long-term capital gains.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This doesn=E2=80=99t work, though. It=E2=80=99=
s too obvious, and=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/34440618.286382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0L=
zI2LzEyNzI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1cac8d1c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the US tax code speci=
fically says</a> that this sort of substitute for interest =E2=80=94=C2=A0c=
alled =E2=80=9Coriginal issue discount=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0gets counted=
 as interest income, not capital gains.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So you have to get away from debt. You can do =
this with stock, but stock doesn=E2=80=99t have a guaranteed return. What y=
ou want is to (1) buy a stock today, (2) <em>hedge the risk of the stock pr=
ice=C2=A0</em>and (3) sell it in a year for 5% more than you paid for it.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This can be done! Classically it is called a =
=E2=80=9Cforward contract.=E2=80=9D You buy a share of stock today for $100=
. You agree to sell it to me, for a fixed price (the =E2=80=9Cstrike price=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cforward price=E2=80=9D), in a year. In a year, I give=
 you the cash and you give me the stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much should I pay you in a year? Well, I s=
hould pay you enough to compensate you for locking up your money for a year=
.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tran=
sparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> If the risk-free interest rate is 5% and the stock doesn=E2=80=99t pay=
 a dividend, I should pay you $105. You put $100 into the stock today, I gi=
ve you $105 in a year, you give me the stock. You have hedged out the stock=
-price risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if the stock goes up to $200 or down to $20=
, you=E2=80=99re selling it for $105 in a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0so you don=E2=
=80=99t need any compensation for risk. You just get paid a risk-free inter=
est rate. But the transaction here is not =E2=80=9Cyou put in $100 today an=
d get back your money with $5 interest in a year=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s =E2=
=80=9Cyou buy stock today and sell it for a profit in a year.=E2=80=9D So, =
plausibly, capital gains. (Not tax or legal advice!)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stock forwards are not particularly usual cont=
racts. But you can=C2=A0<em>build=C2=A0</em>them. The way to build a stock =
forward is by buying a put option and selling a call option. So:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Today, you buy a share of stock for $=
100.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Today, you sell me a call opt=
ion giving me the right (but not the obligation) to buy the stock from you =
for $105 in a year.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Today, you buy=
 from me a put option giving you the right (but not the obligation) to sell=
 me the stock for $105 in a year.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
It is a convenient feature of financial markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0called =E2=
=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34440618.286=
382/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvUHV0JUUyJTgwJTkzY2FsbF9wYXJpdHk=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a83aaea" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">put-call parity</a>=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that the price of the call option you sell equals the price =
of the put option you buy, making your net outlay in Steps 2 and 3 zero, or=
 close to it. (The=C2=A0<em>reason=C2=A0</em>for this is that the combinati=
on of the put and the call is equivalent to a forward contract, struck at t=
he fair forward price, so the price of that forward =E2=80=94=C2=A0or the o=
ptions that make it up =E2=80=94=C2=A0should be zero.)</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">In a year, if the stock is above $105, I exercise the =
call option and buy the stock from you for $105. If it=E2=80=99s below $105=
, you exercise the put option and sell me the stock for $105.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In any case, you put in $100 toda=
y ($100 for the stock, plus the price of the put, minus the offsetting pric=
e of the call) and get back $105 in a year.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">In other words, you got 5% interest on your $100.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Buying the stock makes you long the stock. Buy=
ing the put and selling the call make=C2=A0you =E2=80=9Csynthetically short=
=E2=80=9D the stock: Owning a put and selling a call is economically equiva=
lent to selling the stock forward. If you are long the stock and short the =
forward, then you have no stock price risk. You=E2=80=99re just locking up =
your money in a risk-free trade for a year, and you get paid the risk-free =
interest rate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a variation that is more compli=
cated visually but a bit simpler operationally:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t buy any stock.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You buy a put option and sell a call o=
ption, each with a strike price of $105. The net cost of these options is z=
ero, just as it was above.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You sel=
l a put option and buy a call option, each with a strike price of, say, $55=
. This gives you the right to buy the stock for $55 in a year, and it gives=
 me the right to sell you the stock for $55 in a year.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">The net cost of those options (the ones in Step 3) is,=
 let=E2=80=99s say, $47.60.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In a y=
ear, if the stock is above $105, then I exercise my $105 call option (and b=
uy the stock from you at $105), and you exercise your call option (and buy =
the stock from me at $55), and the net result is that you get $50 (and no s=
tock).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the stock is below $55, =
then I exercise my put option (and sell you the stock at $55), and you exer=
cise your put option (and sell me the stock at $105), and the net result is=
 that you get $50 (and no stock).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
If the stock is between $55 and $105, then you exercise your put option (an=
d sell me the stock at $105)=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>your call option (and b=
uy the stock from me at $55), and the net result is that you get $50 (and n=
o stock).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In any case, you paid $4=
7.60 today (for the options in Step 3) and got back $50 in a year.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In other words, you got 5% interest on you=
r $47.60.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The actual prices don=E2=80=99t matter much; t=
he point is that you have put in some money today in exchange for a fixed a=
mount of money in the future, using options. You get synthetically short (i=
n Step 2), just like in the previous example. But instead of getting long b=
y buying the stock, you get synthetically long=C2=A0by buying the call and =
selling the put (in Step 3). You are long=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>short the =
stock using options.=C2=A0This is neater because rather than buying stock=
=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>options, you do everything in one place, in the opt=
ions market. This is called a =E2=80=9Cbox spread.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does it turn interest income into capital gain=
s? Sure, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34440618.=
286382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubW9ybmluZ3N0YXIuY29tL3BvcnRmb2xpb3MvdGF4LWF3YXJlLWFs=
dGVybmF0aXZlLWNhc2g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a61bf3f" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> more or les=
s</a>. Not legal advice!=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/34440618.286382/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbHBoYWFyY2hpdGVjdC5jb20vMjAyMy8wNS9=
ib3gtc3ByZWFkcy1hbi1hbHRlcm5hdGl2ZS10by10cmVhc3VyeS1iaWxscy8/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB698b0da8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> Alpha Architect says</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The taxation of box spreads is com=
plex; the tax rates (e.g., 25% or 40%) and tax character (e.g., income vs. =
capital gain) of options can differ from the taxation of treasury bills. Th=
e situation can get even more complex for index options, such as SPX, which=
 are considered 1256 contracts, meaning 60% of their gains are taxed at lon=
g-term capital gains rates, and 40% are taxed at short-term capital gains r=
ates.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But let=E2=80=99s just loosely say that, yes, =
this transmutes a thing called =E2=80=9Cinterest=E2=80=9D into capital gain=
s on some equity derivatives. And in fact <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/34440618.286382/aHR0cHM6Ly9tb29udG93ZXJtZXRhLmNvbS9=
ib3h4LWFjY2Vzcy1vcHRpb25zLWZ1bmRpbmctcmF0ZXMtaW4tYW4tZXRmLw/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBb42355ab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> derivatives traders</a> think of box spreads=
 as a way to lend money in the options market=C2=A0and get paid roughly the=
 risk-free interest rate.=C2=A0And that=E2=80=99s what BOXX does: It mostly=
 buys box spreads on the S&amp;P 500 index, earning Treasury-like interest =
through equity index derivatives.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is one other nice feature of box spreads=
 using US listed options. I talked above about you trading options with me.=
=C2=A0But of course if you buy a put option from me today, and then in a ye=
ar you exercise the option and demand that I pay you for the stock, there i=
s some risk that I won=E2=80=99t have the money. Trading US listed options =
solves this problem, because in listed options your counterparty is not me =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0some guy whose credit is risky =E2=80=94=C2=A0but rather the=
 Options Clearing Corp., which backs all US listed options trades. The OCC =
is not actually an agency of the US government, and its credit is not exact=
ly identical to that of US Treasury bills. But you might nonetheless feel p=
retty confident in its credit: It is a too-big-to-fail financial-markets ut=
ility with a strong credit rating and a lot of regulatory interest. =E2=80=
=9CThe OCC is a SIFMU, or systematically important financial market utility=
, which means the federal reserve will (most likely) get involved if someth=
ing is amiss at the OCC,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/34440618.286382/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbHBoYWFyY2hpdGVjdC5jb20vMjAyMy8=
wNS9ib3gtc3ByZWFkcy1hbi1hbHRlcm5hdGl2ZS10by10cmVhc3VyeS1iaWxscy8/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cC698b0da8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Gray writes</a> on Alpha Architect=E2=80=
=99s blog. Lending money in the box spread market pays roughly Treasury-lik=
e interest, and has roughly Treasury-like credit risk. Which is what you wa=
nted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So far, so good, you have turned interest inco=
me into capital gains. But that only does so much. If you know that you wan=
t to lock up your money for 18 months and get paid the risk-free interest r=
ate on it, then, yes, you can buy an 18-month box spread and (perhaps) turn=
 your interest income into long-term capital gains.=C2=A0But that=E2=80=99s=
 not a great=C2=A0<em>product</em>. What you want in a product is something=
 more flexible:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The product lasts forever and is cons=
tantly earning the short-term risk-free interest rate on whatever money it =
holds.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Anyone can put money in or =
take money out at any time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They p=
ay taxes only when they take their money out, and only on their gains (the =
difference between what they take out and what they put in).</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For that you need some ETF technology. Mider w=
rites:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">ETFs=E2=80=99 tax advantage stems from their a=
bility to avoid capital gains. That=E2=80=99s the kind of taxable event tha=
t happens when you sell something for more than you paid. A 1969 law allows=
 a certain type of investment fund to avoid those events if it hands apprec=
iated securities, rather than cash, to an investor withdrawing from the fun=
d =E2=80=94 a transaction known as in-kind redemption. The tax break was ra=
rely used until ETFs were invented two decades later.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thanks to the tax treatment of in-kind redempt=
ions, ETFs typically record no gains at all. That means the tax hit from wi=
nning stock bets is postponed until the investor sells the ETF, a perk hold=
ers of mutual funds, hedge funds and individual brokerage accounts don=E2=
=80=99t typically enjoy.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/34440618.286382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMjkvZGVhbHMtb24tdGhlLXRyYWluLWFyZS1ldmVyeW9uZS1=
zLWJ1c2luZXNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjIyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4fdb899" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about this trea=
tment</a> in the past: US exchange-traded funds ordinarily do not buy or se=
ll stocks. Instead, when you want to buy shares of (say) an S&amp;P 500 ind=
ex ETF, you buy the shares from an arbitrageur, who buys them from an =E2=
=80=9Cauthorized participant,=E2=80=9D a big bank or trading firm,=C2=A0who=
 then=C2=A0<em>creates=C2=A0</em>them with the ETF: The authorized particip=
ant buys all the stocks in the underlying index and delivers them to the ET=
F in exchange for some new shares of the ETF. And when you want to sell, yo=
u sell to an arbitrageur, who sells to an authorized participant, who=C2=A0=
<em>redeems=C2=A0</em>the shares from the ETF: The authorized participant h=
ands the shares back to the ETF and gets back the basket of underlying stoc=
ks, which it then sells.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The key advantage of this is that those=C2=A0<=
em>in-kind redemptions=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0when the ETF takes back sha=
res and gives out its underlying holdings =E2=80=94=C2=A0are not taxable ev=
ents under US law. So a well-run stock index ETF might never have=C2=A0any =
taxable gains, which means that its holders never have any taxable income f=
rom holding the ETF. (Unlike a regular mutual fund, which will have gains w=
henever it sells appreciated stocks, and which will pass those gains on to =
its holders.) When the holders sell their ETF shares, that is a taxable tra=
nsaction for them; if the ETF shares have gone up, then they pay capital ga=
ins taxes on their gains. But just=C2=A0<em>holding=C2=A0</em>the ETF shoul=
dn=E2=80=99t generate taxes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose in theory BOXX could work something =
like that: It could never buy or sell box spreads, but instead have an auth=
orized participant buy the box spreads and exchange them for new ETF shares=
. In practice, that seems more challenging to pull off with index options t=
han it is with stocks, and BOXX does something different. Mider:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earning bond-like returns but recording them a=
s capital gains from options bets, rather than interest, gives BOXX a chanc=
e to deploy the tax magic of ETFs. It does that by turning a single stock i=
nto a perpetual tax-loss-generating machine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The stock that BOXX uses for this task is usua=
lly Booking Holdings Inc., the owner of reservation websites like Priceline=
, OpenTable and Booking.com. In addition to placing box spreads on the S&am=
p;P 500, from time to time BOXX will also buy one on Booking shares. Bookin=
g=E2=80=99s unusually high price, which hasn=E2=80=99t dipped below $3,000 =
this year, makes it an attractive stock for these trades, Gray said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although Booking spreads typically represent l=
ess than 1% of BOXX=E2=80=99s holdings, they play a key role in its tax pla=
nning. A box spread is akin to making two bets, one that a stock or index w=
ill go up, and one that it will go down. Since the bets are symmetrical, th=
e overall value of the spread is unaffected by market movements. But the in=
dividual components are: If Booking rises, the long bet will gain in value,=
 and the short one will lose.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Whenever BOXX wants to cancel out some capital=
 gains, it uses an in-kind redemption to hand off the winning leg of the Bo=
oking trade to a market maker, Gray said. It keeps the losing leg on its ow=
n books, generating a tax loss. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A relatively small investment in Booking, comb=
ined with the ETF loophole, can easily generate large tax losses. Last May,=
 BOXX bought a box spread on Booking for about $1 million. Three months lat=
er, the long side of the trade had gained more than $30 million and the sho=
rt side had lost almost the same amount.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then BOXX shed the winning part of the trade t=
hrough an in-kind redemption and kept the losing part on its books. The fun=
d=E2=80=99s daily holding reports show that the maneuver positioned BOXX to=
 book a tax loss of about $32 million, even though its overall bets on Book=
ing made a few thousand dollars. That loss is more than all the actual retu=
rns the fund earned last year.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A box spread is a synthetic long position in a=
 stock plus a synthetic short position in the stock. If the stock goes up, =
you make money on the long and lose money on the short; if it goes down, yo=
u lose money on the long and make money on the short. You sell the losing l=
eg =E2=80=94=C2=A0generating a tax loss =E2=80=94=C2=A0and redeem the winni=
ng leg in-kind, avoiding a taxable gain. You do that with your weird little=
 side trade in Booking, and you can generate enough tax losses to shield al=
l of your actual (net) gains on your S&amp;P 500 box spreads. And then you =
have a money-market fund whose interest is not taxable. Pretty good!</p>
